message_text:
<paper>
Paper Title: Quantum complexity of time evolution with chaotic Hamiltonians
Paper Abstract: We study the quantum complexity of time evolution in large-N chaotic systems, with the SYK model as our main example. This complexity is expected to increase linearly for exponential time prior to saturating at its maximum value, and is related to the length of minimal geodesics on the manifold of unitary operators that act on Hilbert space. Using the Euler-Arnold formalism, we demonstrate that there is always a geodesic between the identity and the time evolution operator e -iHt whose length grows linearly with time. This geodesic is minimal until there is an obstruction to its minimality, after which it can fail to be a minimum either locally or globally. We identify a criterion — the Eigenstate Complexity Hypothesis (ECH) — which bounds the overlap between offdiagonal energy eigenstate projectors and the k-local operators of the theory, and use it to argue that the linear geodesic will at least be a local minimum for exponential time. We show numerically that the large-N SYK model (which is chaotic) satisfies ECH and thus has no local obstructions to linear growth of complexity for exponential time, as expected from holographic duality. In contrast, we also study the case with N = 2 fermions (which is integrable) and find short-time linear complexity growth followed by oscillations. Our analysis relates complexity to familiar properties of physical theories like their spectra and the structure of energy eigenstates and has implications for the hypothesized computational complexity class separations PSPACE * BQP/poly and PSPACE * BQSUBEXP/subexp, and the “fast-forwarding” of quantum Hamiltonians.
</paper>

<paper_classification>
"contribution" = proposes something new (method, technique, dataset, framework, benchmark, etc.)
"survey" = literature review, overview, meta-analysis, position papers (only references existing work)
</paper_classification>

<entity_types>
task      - Problem being solved (image classification, theorem proving, protein folding)
method    - Technique, algorithm, procedure (gradient descent, CRISPR, induction)
data      - Datasets, databases, benchmarks (ImageNet, MNIST, arXiv corpus)
artifact  - Pre-built: trained models, proof libraries (GPT-4, Mathlib, Cas9)
tool      - Software, instruments, platforms (PyTorch, Lean prover, microscope)
concept   - Abstract ideas, theories, frameworks (attention, category theory)
other     - Entities that don't fit above categories
</entity_types>

<relations>
uses     - Anything EXISTING that the paper uses (methods, datasets, tools, concepts, tasks)
proposes - Anything NEW/NOVEL that the paper creates or introduces

VALIDATION REQUIREMENTS:
- ALL papers MUST have at least 1 "uses" (papers always build on existing work)
- CONTRIBUTION papers MUST have at least 1 "proposes" (they must create something new)
</relations>

A Hilbert space is a real or complex inner product space that is also a complete metric space with respect to the metric induced by the inner product.(no content)It generalizes the notion of Euclidean space to infinite dimensions.(no content)The inner product allows lengths and angles to be defined.

### Key Features

Completeness means that there are enough limits in the space to allow the techniques of calculus to be used.(no content)A Hilbert space is a special case of a Banach space.(no content)Geometric intuition plays a role in Hilbert space theory, with exact analogs of the Pythagorean theorem and parallelogram law holding in a Hilbert space.

### History

Hilbert spaces were studied beginning in the first decade of the 20th century by David Hilbert, Erhard Schmidt, and Frigyes Riesz.(no content)John von Neumann coined the term Hilbert space for the abstract concept that underlies many of these diverse applications.

### Applications

Hilbert spaces are indispensable tools in the theories of partial differential equations, quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis (which includes applications to signal processing and heat transfer), and ergodic theory (which forms the mathematical underpinning of thermodynamics).(no content)In quantum mechanics, the states of a quantum mechanical system are vectors in a certain Hilbert space, the observables are hermitian operators on that space, the symmetries of the system are unitary operators, and measurements are orthogonal projections.

Here are the key findings about Quantum Complexity:

## Overview

Quantum complexity theory is the subfield of computational complexity theory that deals with complexity classes defined using quantum computers, a computational model based on quantum mechanics.

## Main Research Goals

One of the main aims of quantum complexity theory is to find out how these classes relate to classical complexity classes such as P, NP, BPP, and PSPACE.(no content)One of the reasons quantum complexity theory is studied are the implications of quantum computing for the modern Church-Turing thesis, with questions arising about whether the Church-Turing thesis holds for the quantum computation model.

## Key Complexity Classes

Several important complexity classes have been defined for quantum computing:

- Exact quantum polynomial time (EQP) is the class of decision problems that can be solved by a quantum computer with zero error probability and in guaranteed worst-case polynomial time.

- A language is in BQP if there exists a polynomial quantum Turing machine that accepts it with an error probability of at most 1/3 for all instances.

- QIP (Quantum Interactive Proof) is the quantum computing analogue of the classical complexity class IP, which is the set of problems solvable by an interactive proof system with a polynomial-time verifier and one computationally unbounded prover.

## Potential Advantages

One major advantage of using a quantum computational system instead of a classical one is that a quantum computer may be able to give a polynomial time algorithm for some problem for which no classical polynomial time algorithm exists.

Based on the search results, here's comprehensive information about unitary operators:

## Definition

A unitary operator is a bounded linear operator U : H → H on a Hilbert space H that preserves the inner product of the Hilbert space. More specifically, unitary operators are just automorphisms of Hilbert spaces, i.e., they preserve the structure (the vector space structure, the inner product, and hence the topology) of the space on which they act.

## Key Properties

Unitary matrices have significant importance in quantum mechanics because they preserve norms, and thus, probability amplitudes. Additionally, multiplication by U preserves inner products; that is, ⟨Ux, Uy⟩ = ⟨x, y⟩.

## Examples

Several important examples of unitary operators include:

- Rotations in R2 are the simplest nontrivial example of unitary operators. Rotations do not change the length of a vector or the angle between two vectors
- The Fourier operator is a unitary operator, i.e. the operator that performs the Fourier transform (with proper normalization)
- Quantum logic gates are unitary operators

## Applications

In quantum physics, unitarity is the condition that the time evolution of a quantum state according to the Schrödinger equation is mathematically represented by a unitary operator. This is a fundamental concept in quantum mechanics where unitary operators ensure that quantum systems evolve while preserving probability.

Based on the search results, here's comprehensive information about energy eigenstates:

## Definition

An energy eigenstate is an eigenvector of the energy operator (instead of a quantum superposition of different energies).(no content)It is also called an energy eigenvector, energy eigenfunction, or energy eigenket.

## Key Characteristics

A stationary state (energy eigenstate) is a quantum state with all observables independent of time.(no content)The measurable values of the energy of a quantum system are given by the eigenvalues of the Hamiltonian operator, while its eigenstates give the possible energy states of the system.

## Time Evolution

Energy eigenstates are solutions to the time-independent Schrödinger equation; a stationary state is a standing wave that oscillates with an overall complex phase factor, and its oscillation angular frequency is equal to its energy divided by Planck's constant. However, all observable properties of the state are in fact constant in time.

## Properties of Degenerate Energy Levels

A value of energy is said to be degenerate if there exist at least two linearly independent energy states associated with it. Moreover, any linear combination of two or more degenerate eigenstates is also an eigenstate of the Hamiltonian operator corresponding to the same energy eigenvalue.

## Applications

Energy eigenstates are fundamental in quantum mechanics and appear in many contexts, including the quantum harmonic oscillator, particle-in-a-box problems, and the eigenstate thermalization hypothesis used to understand how isolated quantum systems reach thermal equilibrium.

Based on the search results, here's information about the SYK model:

## Overview

The Sachdev–Ye–Kitaev (SYK) model is an exactly solvable model initially proposed by Subir Sachdev and Jinwu Ye, and later modified by Alexei Kitaev to the present commonly used form.

## Significance

The model is believed to bring insights into the understanding of strongly correlated materials and it also has a close relation with the discrete model of AdS/CFT. Additionally, a connection between the structure of quantum entanglement in the SYK model and in black holes was first proposed by Sachdev in 2010, and these connections have led to developments in the quantum theory of black holes.

## Applications

Many condensed matter systems, such as quantum dot coupled to topological superconducting wires, graphene flake with irregular boundary, and kagome optical lattice with impurities, are proposed to be modeled by it.(no content)Some variants of the model are amenable to digital quantum simulation, with pioneering experiments implemented in nuclear magnetic resonance.

The SYK model has become an important theoretical framework connecting condensed matter physics, quantum information, and black hole physics.

## Holographic Duality

Based on the search results, here's an overview of holographic duality:

### Definition and Core Concept

The AdS/CFT correspondence is often described as a "holographic duality" because this relationship between the two theories is similar to the relationship between a three-dimensional object and its image as a hologram.(no content)Although a hologram is two-dimensional, it encodes information about all three dimensions of the object it represents. In the same way, theories that are related by the AdS/CFT correspondence are conjectured to be exactly equivalent, despite living in different numbers of dimensions.

### The Holographic Principle

The holographic principle is a property of string theories and a supposed property of quantum gravity that states that the description of a volume of space can be thought of as encoded on a lower-dimensional boundary to the region.(no content)The holographic principle states that the entropy of ordinary mass is proportional to surface area and not volume; that volume itself is illusory and the universe is really a hologram.

### Historical Development

First proposed by Gerard 't Hooft in 1993, it was given a precise string theoretic interpretation by Leonard Susskind, who combined his ideas with previous ones of 't Hooft and Charles Thorn.(no content)The AdS/CFT correspondence was first proposed by Juan Maldacena in late 1997.

### Significance and Applications

The duality represents a major advance in understanding of string theory and quantum gravity because it provides a non-perturbative formulation of string theory with certain boundary conditions and is the most successful realization of the holographic principle.(no content)Much of the usefulness of the duality results from a strong-weak duality: when the fields of the quantum field theory are strongly interacting, the ones in the gravitational theory are weakly interacting and thus more mathematically tractable.

Based on the search results, here's comprehensive information about the PSPACE complexity class:

## Definition

PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.(no content)Allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power. Because of Savitch's theorem, NPSPACE is equivalent to PSPACE, essentially because a deterministic Turing machine can simulate a nondeterministic Turing machine without needing much more space.

## Key Properties

The class PSPACE is closed under operations union, complementation, and Kleene star.(no content)The complements of all problems in PSPACE are also in PSPACE, meaning that co-PSPACE = PSPACE.

## Alternative Characterizations

An alternative characterization of PSPACE is the set of problems decidable by an alternating Turing machine in polynomial time, sometimes called APTIME or just AP.(no content)A major result of complexity theory is that PSPACE can be characterized as all the languages recognizable by a particular interactive proof system, the one defining the class IP.

## Relationship to Other Complexity Classes

The relations known between PSPACE and the complexity classes NL, P, NP, PH, EXPTIME and EXPSPACE are: NL ⊆ P ⊆ NP ⊆ PH ⊆ PSPACE and PSPACE ⊆ EXPTIME ⊆ EXPSPACE.(no content)The containments NL ⊂ PSPACE and PSPACE ⊂ EXPSPACE are both known to be strict, which follows from the space hierarchy theorem and Savitch's theorem.

## PSPACE-Complete Problems

The hardest problems in PSPACE are the PSPACE-complete problems.(no content)Problems known to be PSPACE-complete include determining properties of regular expressions and context-sensitive grammars, determining the truth of quantified Boolean formulas, step-by-step changes between solutions of combinatorial optimization problems, and many puzzles and games.

## Overview

The Euler–Arnold equations are a class of partial differential equations (PDEs) that describe the geodesic flow on infinite-dimensional Lie groups equipped with right-invariant metrics.(no content)These equations generalize classical mechanical systems, such as rigid body motion and ideal fluid flow (Euler equation), by interpreting their evolution as geodesic flow on a group of transformations.

## Historical Development

Introduced by Vladimir Arnold in 1966, this perspective unifies diverse PDEs arising in fluid dynamics, elasticity, and other areas, in a common geometrical framework.(no content)A rigorous formulation of the Euler–Arnold framework was given by Ebin and Marsden (1970).

## Main Concept

The main idea of Euler–Arnold theory is to geometrically interpret ODEs on infinite-dimensional manifolds as PDEs (and vice-versa).

## Applications

In hydrodynamics, they serve the purpose of describing the motion of inviscid, incompressible fluids.(no content)Many PDEs from fluid dynamics are just special cases of the Euler–Arnold equation when viewed from suitable Lie groups: Burgers' equation, Korteweg–De Vries equation, Camassa–Holm equation, Hunter–Saxton equation, and many more.

## Definition

BQP (bounded-error quantum polynomial time) is the class of decision problems solvable by a quantum computer in polynomial time, with an error probability of at most 1/3 for all instances.(no content)It is the quantum analogue to the complexity class BPP.

## Key Characteristics

The choice of 1/3 in the definition is arbitrary, as you can run the algorithm a constant number of times and take a majority vote to achieve any desired probability of correctness less than 1.

## Relationship to Other Complexity Classes

BQP is contained within PSPACE; that is, the class of problems that can be efficiently solved by quantum computers includes all problems that can be efficiently solved by deterministic classical computers but does not include any problems that cannot be solved by classical computers with polynomial space resources.(no content)It is suspected that BQP is a strict superset of P, meaning there are problems that are efficiently solvable by quantum computers that are not efficiently solvable by deterministic classical computers, such as integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem.(no content)The exact relationship of BQP to P, NP, and PSPACE is not known.(no content)BQP is a subset of PP.

## Practical Significance

BQP is the most useful quantum complexity class and represents the class of decision problems that can be solved in polynomial time by a universal quantum computer.

## What is Chaos Theory?

Chaos theory states that within the apparent randomness of chaotic complex systems, there are underlying patterns, interconnection, constant feedback loops, repetition, self-similarity, fractals and self-organization.(no content)This behavior is known as deterministic chaos, or simply chaos.

## Key Characteristics of Chaotic Systems

Chaos theory describes the behavior of certain dynamical systems – that is, systems whose state evolves with time – that may exhibit dynamics that are highly sensitive to initial conditions (popularly referred to as the butterfly effect). Importantly, these systems are deterministic, meaning that their future behavior follows a unique evolution and is fully determined by their initial conditions, with no random elements involved. In other words, despite the deterministic nature of these systems, this does not make them predictable.

## Practical Limitations

Small differences in initial conditions, such as those due to errors in measurements or due to rounding errors in numerical computation, can yield widely diverging outcomes for such dynamical systems, rendering long-term prediction of their behavior impossible in general.

## Real-World Examples

Chaotic behavior exists in many natural systems, including fluid flow, heartbeat irregularities, weather and climate. It also occurs spontaneously in some systems with artificial components, such as road traffic.

## Applications

Chaos theory has applications in a variety of disciplines, including meteorology, anthropology, sociology, environmental science, computer science, engineering, economics, ecology, and pandemic crisis management.

Chaos theory has applications in a variety of disciplines, including meteorology, anthropology, sociology, environmental science, computer science, engineering, economics, ecology, and pandemic crisis management.

Based on the Wikipedia search results, here's what you should know about the Euler–Arnold equation:

The Euler–Arnold equations are a class of partial differential equations (PDEs) that describe the geodesic flow on infinite-dimensional Lie groups equipped with right-invariant metrics.(no content)These equations generalize classical mechanical systems, such as rigid body motion and ideal fluid flow (Euler equation), by interpreting their evolution as geodesic flow on a group of transformations.(no content)Introduced by Vladimir Arnold in 1966, this perspective unifies diverse PDEs arising in fluid dynamics, elasticity, and other areas, in a common geometrical framework.

**Applications and Significance:**

In hydrodynamics, they serve the purpose of describing the motion of inviscid, incompressible fluids.(no content)Many PDEs from fluid dynamics are just special cases of the Euler–Arnold equation when viewed from suitable Lie groups: Burgers' equation, Korteweg–De Vries equation, Camassa–Holm equation, Hunter–Saxton equation, and many more.(no content)Euler–Arnold theory's main idea is to geometrically interpret ODEs on infinite-dimensional manifolds as PDEs (and vice-versa).
